Introduction

Over the years the earthquakes have been recorded by different organisations in Turkey. Bogazici University, as the most successful university in Turkey, has a earthquake research center and they collected up all the data during the years. They have the most technological devices to uncover the specifications about the earthquakes. The data was collected from the database with particular filters.

The data covers up all the recorded earthquakes in the latitudes between 25 - 50; longitudes 15 - 60. As the metering stations are placed in Turkey most of the recorded earthquakes are in latitudes between 35 - 45; longitudes 25 - 45. The database search time filter was set to dates 27/09/1910 to 27/09/2017. As there are too many earthquakes which have intensities smaller than 4.0, the filter of intensity was set to 3.5 to 9.0 (there was no earthquakes recorded larger than 9.0 intensity). Not being an earthquake specilist or geologist, I have no idea about the different kind of intensity measurements in the dataset (the columns between xM and Ms).

https://www.kaggle.com/caganseval/earthquake/home

Variable definitions

This data is about earthquakes in 1910-2017, Turkey.

  • “id”: the casenumber of earthquakes
  • “data” & “time”: the time of earthquakes
  • “lat” & “long”: the latitude and longitude of earthquakes
  • “counrey”, “city”, “area”: the place of earthquakes
  • “direction”: the direction of earthquake
  • “dist” & “depth”: the distance and depth of direction in km
  • “xm”, “md”, “richter”, “mw”, “ms”, “mb”: the different kind of intensity measurements of earthquakes

Data Cleaning

Dealing with date - year

year_date <- ymd(using_data$date) %>% format("%Y")
head(year_date)
## [1] "2003" "2007" "1978" "1997" "2000" "2005"
year_table <- table(year_date)
head(year_table)
## year_date
## 1910 1911 1912 1913 1914 1915 
##    1    6   18   12   29   20

Dealing with date - month

month_date <- ymd(using_data$date) %>% format("%m")
head(month_date)
## [1] "05" "08" "05" "03" "04" "01"
table(month_date)
## month_date
##   01   02   03   04   05   06   07   08   09   10   11   12 
## 1955 1744 2243 2036 2285 2129 2036 1902 1777 2301 1931 1668
month_date_factor <- as.factor(month_date)
month_levels <- c("Jan.", "Feb.", "Mar.", "Apr.", "May", "Jun.", "Jul.", "Aug.", "Sept.", "Oct.", "Nov.", "Dec.")
levels(month_date_factor) <- month_levels
month_date_factor <- ordered(month_date_factor)
head(month_date_factor)
## [1] May  Aug. May  Mar. Apr. Jan.
## 12 Levels: Jan. < Feb. < Mar. < Apr. < May < Jun. < Jul. < ... < Dec.
month_table <- table(month_date_factor)
head(month_table)
## month_date_factor
## Jan. Feb. Mar. Apr.  May Jun. 
## 1955 1744 2243 2036 2285 2129
using_data$month <- as.vector(month_date_factor)

Direction - radar chart

maxmin <- data.frame(north = c(2500, 0), north_west = c(2500, 0), west = c(2500, 0),
                     south_west = c(2500, 0), south = c(2500, 0), south_east = c(2500, 0), 
                     east = c(2500, 0),north_east = c(2500, 0))
dir <- data.frame(north = 576, north_west = 2019, west = 497, south_west = 2011, south = 605, 
                  south_east = 1917, east = 536,north_east = 1901)
dir2 <- rbind(maxmin,dir)
radarchart(dir2, axistype = 0, seg = 5, centerzero = T, title = "Direction-Radar Chart", 
           pfcol = "yellow")

The Relationship Between Month, Latitude And Longitude

ggplot(data = using_data) + geom_point(mapping = aes(x = lat, y = long)) + facet_wrap(~ month)

Conclusion

  1. the number of earthquake trend to increase
  2. the number of earthquake has little difference every month
  3. earthquakes always happen at 12 - 13 o’clock, sometimes at 1 - 2 o’clock
  4. the most of earthquakes are happen in latitude: 30 - 48, longitude: 20 - 48
  5. the most of earthquakes happen in four orientation: northwest, northeast, southwest, southeast
  6. the most of earthquakes happen within 11 meters
  7. the most of earthquakes happen with rither at 3 - 5
  8. the place of earthquake is no relationship with month
